{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"073c8c48-fd7b-4aa1-a3c7-c0865aab2ec3","content":"Here are the **evaluation performance issues** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions executes during *evaluation* (before any targets run), blocking the MSBuild engine. This is expensive and non-cacheable — it runs on every evaluation, including IDE design-time builds.\n\n**Fix:** Move file reading into a target with `Inputs/Outputs`, or use a custom task during execution instead.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis walks the *entire* directory tree during evaluation. As the project grows (or if `node_modules`, `.git`, or large artifact folders exist), this becomes increasingly expensive.\n\n**Fix:** Narrow the glob to specific extensions/directories, or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (Low-Medium Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of chained imports. Currently small, but this pattern scales poorly — each import adds an evaluation pass. In larger repos this compounds significantly.\n\n**Fix:** Flatten where possible, or consolidate into a single `.props` file.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Issue | Severity | Location |\n|-------|----------|----------|\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | 🔴 High | Line 13 |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | 🟡 Medium | Line 9 |\n| 3-level import chain | 🟢 Low | `imports/` |\n\nThe file I/O property function is the most critical — eliminate it first for the biggest evaluation speedup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0bdb2e2d-5c2d-4f26-a311-042e580d5103","outputTokens":492,"requestId":"7402:3C1523:1D7793B:20973